TI  - Simulation of memetics by means of Knowledge Attributed Petri Nets
PY  - 2008
T2  - Summer Computer Simulation Conference 2008, SCSC 2008, Part of the 2008 Summer Simulation Multiconference, SummerSim 2008
SP  - 487
EP  - 493
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-80052068052&partnerID=40&md5=0ec9fbf820845a7245be7ef275a8fa8d
AD  - McLeod Institute of Simulation Sciences, Hungarian Center, Budapest University of Technology and Economics, H-1111 Budapest, Sztoczek u. 4., Hungary
AB  - It is a commonplace to say that we are living in an information society and usually the emphasis is on the up-to-date hardware and software applied. Nevertheless the human factor can be decisive in a large number of cases. Independently of the means provided by technology human behavior influences the propagation of information decisively. A realistic description of the propagation of information in human society can adequately be described by memetics [1][2] that means that information is propagated from one human being to the other similarly to the spreading of viruses or genes. Human beings form a network where the nodes are interconnected. Some of these nodes modify the information packages received and propagate them to other nodes to which they are connected directly. Some other nodes forward the information packages to the neighboring nodes unmodified, while some do not propagate them further. This mechanism matches the human relations where reliability, friendship, antipathy, etc. play an important role in communication [3][4]. In order to obtain insight into the operation and behavior of such systems simulation may be applied. In the present contribution it is shown how such systems can effectively be simulated using Knowledge Attributed Petri Nets [5].
