AD  - University of Bari Aldo Moro, Italy
AB  - The purpose of the study is to understand the role of memetics in fanvid production and what kind of practices and types of media result from this connection. This study proposes the analysis of the r/LaStalla subreddit that refers to the streamer, YouTuber, and influencer Blur. This is the space for fandom content production, to which live reactions are made once a week on Twitch. Reddit’s participatory cultures are formed and consolidated through irony, play, complex and contradictory modes of aggregation within which the meme production has always played a central role and where vernacular creativity becomes a collective discourse with social functions such as identity construction, accumulation of cultural capital, and negotiation of community affordances and values. From the content creators’ perspective, it has become necessary to preside over the platform by catalyzing fandom and content production within subreddits identified by the practice of “RoastMe,” having users mock and laugh at themselves. This dynamic is based on the acceptance of a humorous framework that crosses norms of what is socially accepted. Just as the roast is based on the unlimited humorous creativity of community members, memetic practice can become a key expression of it because of its constitution as a collective discourse based on infinite communicative jokes through the lens of irony and self-mockery. © 2026 selection and editorial matter, Louisa Ellen Stein and Samantha Close; individual chapters, the contributors.
