AD  - Department of Music and Drama, University of Huddersfield, Queensgate, Huddersfield HD1 3DH, Creative Arts Building, United Kingdom
AB  - The climax of the chorus 'The Heavens are Telling' from Haydn's oratorio Die Schöpfung (The Creation) employs a harmonic progression that Beethoven later adapted to conclude the first movement of his Symphony no. 2. An earlier (pre-Haydn) version of the progression might be found in a keyboard rondo by C. P. E. Bach. This harmonic unit is regarded as consisting of a sequence of musemes (musical memes): each is a replicated pattern serving as the cultural analogue to the gene. The neural encoding of such patterns is considered in terms of William Calvin's hexagonal cloning theory, in order to adduce 'memotypic' (meme-encoding) evidence to support the 'phemotypic' (meme-product) evidence gleaned from musical score-analysis. © Institute of Materials, Minerals and Mining 2012.
