UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-84939211676&doi=10.1093%2Facprof%3Aoso%2F9780192632449.003.0002&partnerID=40&md5=b2cb27646330b03fb5b3af36ed14af1f
AD  - University of the West of England, Bristol, United Kingdom
AB  - Memetics offers novel solutions to old problems, among them the origins and evolution of the human brain, with its specialised language and unique intelligence. Thus, this chapter justifies that memetics can describe an array of developments, including the rise of big brains, culture, consciousness, and notions of self. It also addresses one further issue linked with the definition of memes. It sticks to Dawkins' original formulation of memes as information that is passed on by imitation. It then reports the advantages of the memetic perspective. Memes began driving genes to generate a brain that was especially good at replicating those memes. In addition, it clarifies the implications of the memetic driving hypothesis. In general, it is proposed that taking the memes' eye view will give as dramatic a transformation in the understanding of human nature as taking the genes' eye view has done in evolutionary biology. © Oxford University Press, 2000. All rights reserved.
