UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-105030260207&doi=10.1007%2F978-3-032-00040-8_3&partnerID=40&md5=5196fca764319e25c21e4cf12a46de52
AD  - North Carolina A & T State University, Greensboro, NC, United States
AD  - Regent University, Virginia Beach, VA, United States
AB  - We don’t just like sharing memes. We are biologically driven to share them. In fact, the term “meme” was coined by a biologist Richard Dawkins, who defined it as material that gets replicated and passed on in the social world, like genes are replicated and passed on in the biological world. Just as the most fit genes are passed onto future generations, so too are only the most fit memes passed onto future generations. Although we may think of a meme now as an image/text combo that is quickly shared on social media, memes have always been a part of human interaction. Technology has simply increased the pace in which memes can replicate. This chapter will provide a historic overview of memes to demonstrate how human understanding of memes has developed over time. It will begin in biological studies and the conceptualization of “memetics.” It will then move on to the oral exchange of memes, reviewing research in rumor, gossip, and humor. Then it will transition to the modern conceptualization of memes, which are the digital image/text combinations. The chapter will next transition to an overview of the positive and negative uses of memes, recognizing that while many memes exist to share humor and build positive rapport, many have been used as propaganda. The chapter will conclude with a tie back to memetic theory, discussing why and how memes fulfill our needs equally well for humor and propaganda, and ethical responsibility of meme users. © The Editor(s) (if applicable) and The Author(s), under exclusive license to Springer Nature Switzerland AG 2026.
