TI  - Modulation of growth process by hyperactive antifreeze proteins ensue in synergistic way
PY  - 2025
T2  - Journal of Molecular Liquids
VL  - 439
C7  - 128870
DO  - 10.1016/j.molliq.2025.128870
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-105021263300&doi=10.1016%2Fj.molliq.2025.128870&partnerID=40&md5=06faf101a1a33e03e63c87f0690b4afb
AD  - School of Chemical Sciences, Indian Association for the Cultivation of Science, Jadavpur, Kolkata, 700032, India
AB  - Different aspects of the mechanistic pathway of freeze avoiding process induced by antifreeze proteins (AFPs) have been explored recently. However, detailed understanding of the cooperativity and synergy between antifreeze proteins (AFPs) and growing ice crystals, as well as their origins, remains incomplete. In this article, the cooperativity of the hyperactive insect antifreeze protein (SbwAFP) and the growing ice crystals during the process of ice growth inhibition is systematically investigated and compared with a topologically similar non-antifreeze protein (non-AFP). Estimated growth rates combined with visual inspection of simulations trajectories of growth processes on three different planes (basal, primary prism and secondary prism) of hexagonal ice for systems with no protein, with SbwAFP and with non-AFP reveal two distinct scenarios. At the initial phase, when the distance between IBS of SbwAFP (or a chosen surface of non-AFP) and growing ice front is larger than 1.5 nm, the growth process is found to be similar for all the systems, indicating no influence of proteins. In the next phase, when the distance between is smaller than 1.5 nm, enhancement of growth process for SbwAFP and retardation of growth process for non-AFP when compared to the same for system with no protein were observed, signifying a clear influence of the proteins. A biased movement of SbwAFP towards growing ice front before adsorbing on the surfaces of the ice crystals was observed for all three planes which were found to be synergistically related to the promotion of growth process. On the contrary, such a synergy is found to be absent for non-AFP. Therefore, our results indicate that antifreeze proteins can sense the growing ice front from a certain distance and bind to the ice surface more quickly compared to the other class of proteins by cooperatively promoting the ice growth with the biased movement towards the growing front by itself. Finally, we present a complete stage-wise process of the growth inhibition by AFP which can help design the antifreeze memetics. © 2025 Elsevier B.V.
