TI  - Batik glugu of Boyolali: Structural and memetic approaches
PY  - 2020
T2  - Nusantara's Indigenous Knowledge
SP  - 133
EP  - 151
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85144287584&partnerID=40&md5=f8c3b5d3543960198d7d217db3f4207b
AD  - Universitas Indonesia, Depok, Indonesia
AD  - Philosophy Department, Universitas Indonesia, Depok, Indonesia
AB  - Batik glugu is a type of batik fabric manufactured in the Boyolali regency. The distinct patterns of batik glugu are inspired by patterns in the grain of glugu, the wood from a particular type of coconut tree whose bark can be used to make a cloth (morus papyrifera). Batik glugu as a product of cultural innovation has had to overcome several challenges in order to establish itself as a cultural artifact. We would like to compare structural and memetic approaches to understanding this process. The goal of structural analysis is to examine human relations in terms of the patterns of their social activities. The purpose of memetics analysis is to explain the role of human agents in processes of cultural innovation. This chapter takes a particular phenomenon as its starting point and applies inductive reasoning to their analysis in order to derive general conclusions. We undertake an in-depth analysis of batik glugu by comparing the theoretical approaches of structuralism and memetics. Memetics provides an alternative approach to analyze the evolution of cultural phenomenon. The law of cultural change is as basic as the law of nature. According to structuralist theory, human beings possess an innate motivation to act and innovate, and therefore innovation is seen as an activity. However, the dynamics of innovation can also be understood as the result of cultural memes acting to protect and maintain their sustainability. Thus, culture can be viewed as a living entity. According to the alternative approach of memetics, however, cultural innovations are seen as common. The theory of memetics plays an important role in defining the role of agents and what lies behind them. The tools of structuralism, however, offer an explanation of the phenomenon of batik glugu.that can reveal the factors central to the innovation of batik glugu. Our analysis od batik glugu has a high potential to show that there are dynamic ways of looking at the phenomenon of culture. Culture is not an inert object that simply needs to be maintained, preserved, and safeguarded. Culture is a living entity with the power to control the human mind. © 2020 Nova Science Publishers, Inc.
