AD  - Deutsches Zentrum für Integrations- und Migrationsforschung (DeZIM), Nationaler Diskriminierungs- und Rassismusmonitor (NaDiRa), Mauerstraße 76, Berlin, 10117, Germany
AD  - SOCIUM Forschungszentrum Ungleichheit und Sozialpolitik, Universität Bremen, Mary-Somerville-Straße 9, Bremen, 28359, Germany
AB  - We examine the role of two different forms of social orientations for the integration in adolescent's social networks. On the one hand, the identification with being German represents an aspect of social identity. On the other hand, we regard multiculturalism as a political orientation that diffuses through networks. We test, first, whether, in terms of homophily, the similarity of two individuals regarding these social orientations influences social contacts, and, second, whether these social orientations result from the social influence that persons exert in the friendship network. We use data from the CILS4EU project for our empirical analysis, from which we can use up to 40 networks of a maximum of 875 students to estimate co-evolution models for networks and behavior. The results show that mechanisms of both selection and influence are at work in the identification with being German. For example, on the one hand, a shared social identity increases the chances of contact, and on the other hand, adolescents tend to adapt their social identity to their friends. For multicultural attitudes, we find only the mechanism of influence. Here, the diffusion of these attitudes via social influence in networks essentially plays a role. For the generation of network contacts and thus for social integration, we find no effects. Regarding multicultural attitudes, we find only influence. Hence, with respect to these attitudes there seems to be no homophily. We conclude that unlike the identification with being German, multicultural attitudes are not a salient feature of group identities. © 2024 Nomos Verlagsgesellschaft mbH und Co KG. All rights reserved.
