AD  - Cape Peninsula University of Technology (CPUT), South Africa
AB  - Nature has been designing for millennia. The scientific field of evolutionary biology has made huge breakthroughs in understanding the processes guiding natural design. Evolutionary biology has given rise to the study of memetics and to Universal Darwinism. Cultural ideas and information are increasingly competing with physical environmental conditions and genetic environments as selectors in genetic evolutionary processes. This is very evident when we look at agricultural cultivation, ornamental horticulture and aesthetic landscape design. All of the above professions are paradigm driven and manifest metaphysical ideas as produce, products, new plant hybrids, artefacts, gardens, environments and spaces. This review paper focuses on current aesthetic trends in landscape designs and views these landscapes as phenotypes-physical and visual cluster of information that can be copied, with variation and heredity. Memetic theories of familiarity and distinction will be applied to landscape precedents in literature to find a correlation between the genetic selection pressures of cultural landscape aesthetic on plants in ornamental horticulture. The paper highlights the use of Aloe species in cultural South-African landscapes and explain the hybridisation as a product of a phenotypically landscape aesthetic. Apart from the northern provinces of South Africa, Aloes were until recently not popular ornamental plants in the Western Cape and not seen often in commercial nurseries or private gardens. This seems strange as Aloes are common in South Africa almost defining the natural scenery; Aloes are hardy in landscape application and easily recognizable. Cultural memetic influences are increasingly competing with physical environmental conditions and genetic environments as the main selectors in genetic evolutionary processes.
