AB  - The essay explores the adequacy of the meme' concept to explain the basic mechanism of cultural evolution. Distin's defense of memetics' is deficient because it is based on a flawed analogy with genetics. Although Richerson and Boyd's cultural variant' is not based on a flawed analogy with genetics, their alternative appears primarily to be operant conditioning in disguise and presents no novel innovations in learning theory. Both models of gene—culture co-evolution are examples of one-sided cultural determinism with no genuine biological component. Analysis of the information metaphysics of memes and cultural variants reveals that both concepts are also committed to mind—body dualism. © 2007, Sage Publications. All rights reserved.
